<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-qr-factorization">
  <title>QR Factorization</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      The QR factorization of a matrix is a decomposition of a matrix into the product of an orthogonal matrix and an upper triangular matrix.
      This factorization is useful in solving systems of linear equations, computing eigenvalues, and in numerical linear algebra.
    </p>

    <definition>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The QR factorization of a matrix <m>A</m> is given by
        </p>

        <p>
          <me>
            A = QR
          </me>
          where <m>Q</m> is an orthogonal matrix and <m>R</m> is an upper triangular matrix.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
  </introduction>


  <subsection xml:id="sect-qr-factorization-algorithm">
    <title>QR Factorization Algorithm</title>

    <p>
      The QR-factorization can be performed using the Gram-Schmidt orthogonalization seen in <xref ref="sect-gram-schmidt"/>.
      We will first show this with an example and then explain why this works.
    </p>

    <example xml:id="ex-qr-factor">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Perform Gram-Schmidt Orthogonalization to find an orthonormal set of vectors of the columns of
        </p>

        <p>
          <me>
            A = \begin{bmatrix} -9 \amp 4 \amp 7 \\ -18 \amp 15 \amp -28 \\ 6 \amp 2 \amp 49 \\ \end{bmatrix}
          </me>
        </p>

        <p>
          and then use the resulting matrix <m>Q</m> to find <m>R</m> using
          <me>
            R = Q^{\intercal} A
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>

      <solution>
        <p>
          Let <m>\boldsymbol{a}_j</m> be the columns of <m>A</m> and we will call the resulting orthogonal vectors as <m>\boldsymbol{q}_j</m>.
        </p>

        <p>
          <me>
            \boldsymbol{q}_1 = \frac{\boldsymbol{a}_1}{||\boldsymbol{a}_1||} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{9^2+18^2+6^2}} \begin{bmatrix} -9 \\ -18 \\ 6 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} -3/7 \\ -6/7 \\ 2/7 \end{bmatrix}
          </me>
        </p>

        <p>
          For the second vector,
          <me>
            \begin{aligned} \boldsymbol{u}_2 \amp = \boldsymbol{a}_2 - \langle \boldsymbol{q}_1, \boldsymbol{a}_2 \rangle \boldsymbol{q}_1\\ \amp = \begin{bmatrix} 4 \\ 15 \\ 2 \end{bmatrix} - (-14) \begin{bmatrix} -3/7 \\ -6/7 \\ 2/7 \end{bmatrix}  = \begin{bmatrix} 4 \\ 15 \\ 2 \end{bmatrix} + \begin{bmatrix} -6 \\ -12 \\ 4 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} -2 \\ 3 \\ 6 \end{bmatrix} \end{aligned}
          </me>
          and then this vectors is normalized with
          <me>
            \boldsymbol{q}_2 = \frac{1}{||\boldsymbol{u}_2||} \boldsymbol{u_2} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2^2+3^2+6^2}} \begin{bmatrix} -2 \\ 3 \\ 6 \end{bmatrix} = \frac{1}{7} \begin{bmatrix} -2 \\ 3 \\ 6 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} -2/7 \\ 3/7 \\ 6/7 \end{bmatrix}
          </me>
        </p>

        <p>
          Lastly, the third column of <m>Q</m> can be found with
          <me>
            \begin{aligned} \boldsymbol{u}_3 \amp = \boldsymbol{a}_3 - \langle \boldsymbol{q}_2, \boldsymbol{a}_3 \rangle \boldsymbol{q}_2 - \langle \boldsymbol{q}_1, \boldsymbol{a}_3 \rangle \boldsymbol{q}_1 \\ \amp = \begin{bmatrix} 7 \\ -28 \\ 49 \end{bmatrix} - 28 \begin{bmatrix} -2/7 \\ 3/7 \\ 6/7 \end{bmatrix} - 35 \begin{bmatrix} -3/7 \\ -6/7 \\ 2/7 \end{bmatrix} \\ \amp = \begin{bmatrix} 7 \\ -28 \\ 49 \end{bmatrix} + \begin{bmatrix} 8 \\ -12 \\ -24 \end{bmatrix} + \begin{bmatrix} 15 \\ 30 \\ -10 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 30 \\ -10 \\ 15 \end{bmatrix} \end{aligned}
          </me>
          and lastly, we normalize this vector as
          <me>
            \boldsymbol{q3} = \frac{1}{||\boldsymbol{u}_2||} \boldsymbol{u_2} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{30^2+10^2+15^2}} \begin{bmatrix} 30 \\ -10 \\ 15 \end{bmatrix} = \frac{1}{35} \begin{bmatrix} 30 \\ -10 \\ 15 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 6/7 \\ -2/7 \\ 3/7 \end{bmatrix}
          </me>
          and thus the matrix <m>Q</m> is the matrix with these three vectors or
          <me>
            Q = \begin{bmatrix} -3/7 \amp -2/7 \amp 6/7 \\ -6/7 \amp 3/7 \amp -2/7 \\ 2/7 \amp 6/7 \amp 3/7 \end{bmatrix}
          </me>
        </p>

        <p>
          Lastly, we find <m>R</m> with
          <me>
            \begin{aligned} R \amp = Q^{\intercal} A  \\ \amp = \begin{bmatrix} -3/7 \amp -6/7 \amp 2/7 \\ -2/7 \amp 3/7 \amp 6/7 \\ 6/7 \amp -2/7 \amp 3/7 \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} -9 \amp 4 \amp 7 \\ -18 \amp 15 \amp -28 \\ 6 \amp 2 \amp 49 \end{bmatrix} \\ \amp = \begin{bmatrix} 21 \amp -14 \amp 35 \\ 0 \amp 7 \amp 28 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 35 \\ \end{bmatrix} \end{aligned}
          </me>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <p>
      A natural question to ask is why does this work? Why does the Gram-Schmidt process give us the QR factorization? The answer is that the Gram-Schmidt process gives us an orthonormal basis for the column space of <m>A</m> and thus the matrix <m>Q</m> is an orthogonal matrix.
      Then, the matrix <m>R</m> is the change of basis matrix from the standard basis to the orthonormal basis given by the columns of <m>Q</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      Examining the result of <m>R = Q^{\intercal}A </m>, the matrix <m>Q^{\intercal}</m> projects the columns of <m>A</m> onto <m>Q</m>.
      Because <m>Q</m> is constructed as the
    </p>
  </subsection>


  <subsection xml:id="sect-solving-linear-systems-qr">
    <title>Solving Linear Systems with QR factoring.</title>

    <p>
      We can solving linear systems with the QR factorization and is often done if the original matrix is difficult to solve (Section where this is explained??).
      Let's look the example in <xref ref="sect-solve-linear-system-lu"/>.
    </p>

    <p>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            Write <m>A = QR</m>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            Solve <m>R\boldsymbol{x} = Q^{\intercal}\boldsymbol{b}</m>.
            Note that <m>R</m> is upper triangular and thus this can be solved with back substitution.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </p>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Solve the linear system <m>A\boldsymbol{x}= \boldsymbol{b}</m> using the <m>QR</m>-decomposition where
          <me>
            A = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp -2 \amp 1 \\ 6 \amp 0 \amp 4 \\ -6 \amp -8 \amp -7 \end{bmatrix} \qquad \boldsymbol{b} = \begin{bmatrix} 14 \\ 22 \\ -9 \end{bmatrix}
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>

      <solution>
        <p>
          First, we need to find the factorization.
          We can follow the same steps using Gram-Schmidt Orthogonalization as in <xref ref="ex-qr-factor"/>, however, generally the resulting elements of <m>Q</m> are not rational, so we will resort to software to do this.
          Using Matlab or Julia, the result in
          <me>
            \begin{aligned} Q \amp = \begin{bmatrix} -0.333333  \amp -0.522976  \amp  0.784465 \\ -0.666667  \amp -0.457604  \amp -0.588348 \\ 0.666667  \amp -0.719092  \amp -0.196116 \\ \end{bmatrix} \\ R \amp = \begin{bmatrix} -9.0 \amp  -4.66667 \amp  -7.66667 \\ 0.0 \amp   6.79869 \amp   2.68025 \\ 0.0 \amp   0.0     \amp  -0.196116 \\ \end{bmatrix} \end{aligned}
          </me>
          and this just shows the first 5 or so digits of the two matrices.
        </p>

        <p>
          The next step is to find <m>Q^{\intercal} \boldsymbol{b}</m> or
          <me>
            Q^{\intercal} \boldsymbol{b} = \begin{bmatrix} -25.33333333333333 \\ -10.917131522692245 \\ -0.19611613513818504 \\ \end{bmatrix}
          </me>
        </p>

        <p>
          And lastly, we solve <m>R\boldsymbol{x} = Q^{\intercal} \boldsymbol{b}</m>.
          This is done with back-substitution.
          The result of this is:
          <me>
            \boldsymbol{x} = \begin{bmatrix} 2.999999999999997 \\ -2.000000000000001 \\ 1.0000000000000033 \\ \end{bmatrix}
          </me>
          which is close to the answer found in <xref ref="sect-solve-linear-system-lu"/>, the difference being that here we used floating-point numbers which have round off errors.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>


  <subsection xml:id="sect-qr-eigenvalues">
    <title>Using QR factorization to find Eigenvalues</title>

    <p>
      Another use of <m>QR</m>-factorization is that of numerically estimating the eigenvalues of a matrix.
    </p>

    <lemma xml:id="lem-eigenvalues-qr">
      <statement>
        <p>
          The matrix <m>A = QR</m> for orthogonal matrix <m>Q</m> and upper triangular matrix <m>R</m> has the same eigenvalues as <m>RQ</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>


      <proof>
        <p>
          This amounts to showing that the matrices <m>QR</m> and <m>RQ</m> are similar.
          <me>
            QR = S^{-1} RQ S
          </me>
          Let <m>S = Q^{\intercal}</m> and since <m>Q</m> is orthogonal, then <m>S^{-1} = Q</m>
          <me>
            QR = Q RQ Q^{\intercal} = Q R
          </me>
        </p>
      </proof>
    </lemma>

    <p>
      We use this fact to generate the following algorithm
    </p>

    <algorithm xml:id="alg-qr-eigenvalues">
      <statement>
        <p>
          The following steps generates a sequence of matrices <m>A_k</m>.
          In the limit <m>A_k</m> goes to the diagonal matrix with the eigenvalues of <m>A</m> on the diagonal.
        </p>

        <p>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Let <m>A_0 = A</m> and <m>k=0</m>
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                Factor <m>A_k = Q_k R_k </m> where <m>Q_k</m> is othogonal and <m>R_k</m> is upper triangular.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                Let <m>A_{k+1} = R_k Q_k</m>.
                That is, reverse the order of the matrix multiplies.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                If the maximum of the absolute value of the lower left elements of <m>A_{k+1}</m> is within <m>\epsilon</m>, then stop.
                Otherwise increment <m>k</m> by 1 and return to step 2.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </algorithm>

    <p>
      We will show an example of this in action and then prove later why this converges to the correct answer.
    </p>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Estimate the eigenvalues of the matrix
          <me>
            A = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 3 \amp -2 \amp 6 \\ 2 \amp 1 \amp 3 \end{bmatrix}
          </me>
          as found in <xref ref="ex-eigs-3by3"/>
        </p>
      </statement>

      <solution>
        <p>
          First let <m>A_0=A</m>.
          Then factor <m>A_0</m> into <m>Q_0</m> and <m>R_0</m>, where <m>A_0=Q_0R_0</m>.
          This is done with software.
          If using Julia,
        </p>


        <program language="julia">
          <code>
            QR₀ = qr(A₀)
          </code>
        </program>

        <p>
          and the matrices are then located in <c>Matrix(QR₀.Q)</c><fn>Note: if you leave off the <c>Matrix</c>, then the matrix <c>QR₀.Q</c> is in a compact form.</fn> or
          <cd>
          <cline>3×3 Matrix{Float64}:</cline>
          <cline>-0.267261   0.145479  -0.952579</cline>
          <cline>-0.801784  -0.581914   0.136083</cline>
          <cline>-0.534522   0.800132   0.272166</cline>
          </cd>
          and <c>QR₀.R</c> or
          <cd>
          <cline>3×3 Matrix{Float64}:</cline>
          <cline> -3.74166  1.06904  -6.41427</cline>
          <cline>  0.0      1.96396  -1.09109</cline>
          <cline>  0.0      0.0       1.63299</cline>
          </cd>
        </p>

        <p>
          Then the order of the matrices is reversed to <c>A₁ = QR₀.R * QR₀.Q</c>, resulting in
          <cd>
          <cline>3×3 Matrix{Float64}:</cline>
          <cline>  3.57143   -6.29869   1.96396</cline>
          <cline> -0.99146   -2.01587  -0.0296957</cline>
          <cline> -0.872872   1.30661   0.444444</cline>
          </cd>
        </p>

        <p>
          Recall that the algorithm is supposed to result in an upper triangular matrix <m>A_k</m>.
          We'll do one more step by hand.
          Let <c>QR₁ = qr(A₁)</c>.
          This gives us the two matrices (which we won't show here), but the next <m>A</m> matrix is found by reversing the <m>R</m> and <m>Q</m> with <c>A₂ = QR₁.R * QR₁.Q</c> resulting in
          <cd>
          <cline>3×3 Matrix{Float64}:</cline>
          <cline> 4.65025   -4.45991      -2.88562</cline>
          <cline> 0.830799  -3.49591      -0.700881</cline>
          <cline> 0.199152   0.000981054   0.845661</cline>
          </cd>
        </p>

        <p>
          Notice that the numbers in the lower right are getting smaller, but not very quickly.
          We'll do a number of steps with
        </p>


        <program language="julia">
          <code>
            Aₖ = A
            for i=1:25
              QRₖ = qr(Aₖ)
              Aₖ = QRₖ.R * QRₖ.Q
            end
            Aₖ
          </code>
        </program>

        <p>
          and the result is
        </p>

        <p>
          <cd>
          <cline>3×3 Matrix{Float64}:</cline>
          <cline>  3.99934      -5.00092      3.53563</cline>
          <cline> -0.000921692  -2.99934      0.706641</cline>
          <cline> -2.34445e-15   1.27349e-12  1.0</cline>
          </cd>
        </p>
        <p>
          The terms in the lower left are quite close to zero, so we can estimate that the eigenvalues are the diagonal elements or <c> 3.99934, -2.9934</c> and <c>1.0</c>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
    <p>
      We now discuss why this works.  
    </p>
  </subsection>
</section>